article.headline: Golden Eagles defeat DePaul for sixth straight time
article.linkText: Marquette makes it 10 straight wins at DePaul
article.story: ROSEMONT, Ill. (AP) -- The Marquette players couldn't help but know Louisville had lost, what with the way their large contingent of fans carried on when they heard the score. Just in case, though, coach Tom Crean reminded his players during the next timeout. The Golden Eagles had a chance to go into Saturday's game against No. 2 Louisville as the top team in Conference USA -- provided they beat DePaul first. "I just brought it up and said we've got to start guarding better and rebounding better,'' Crean said. "There was probably a little extra energy after we heard that score.'' Marquette got more aggressive defensively, and Steve Novak made four straight 3-pointers to break the game open in the second half as the 11th-ranked Golden Eagles beat DePaul 73-60 on Wednesday night. Novak finished with a career-high 17 points. Chicago native Dwyane Wade added 17 points, eight assists, seven rebounds and three steals for the Golden Eagles (18-3, 9-1 C-USA), who won their 10th straight. Robert Jackson had 15 points and 10 rebounds, while Todd Townsend had 14 points. "A lot of us were excited to come down to Chicago,'' Wade said. "We knew they were 11-1 at home, they hadn't really lost at home. They beat Cincinnati at home, which is a good road team, so we knew we had to come down here and fight. "That's what we did and now we can look forward to our next game.'' And it's going to be a biggie. Six days after beating then-No. 14 Wake Forest, the Golden Eagles will host Louisville on Saturday. The Cardinals are ranked No. 2 in the country, but they now trail Marquette by a half-game in C-USA's American Division after losing at St. Louis 59-58 earlier Wednesday. "It's going to be an unbelievable matchup,'' Wade said. "It's going to be like last week's game, which they said was like an NCAA atmosphere. This game is going to be the same.'' Sam Hoskin led DePaul with his third double-double of the season (16 points and 12 rebounds), but it wasn't enough to keep the Blue Demons (12-8, 4-5) from losing at home for only the second time this season. Then again, DePaul didn't exactly have a homecourt advantage at Allstate Arena on Wednesday night. Marquette fans made up about three-quarters of the crowd of 11,154, and they were a rowdy, raucous bunch. With about 1½ minutes left, DePaul fans were heading for the exits while the Marquette fans were on their feet, chanting, "This is our house.'' Marquette has won its last six against DePaul, and hasn't lost in Chicago since January 1999. "To have that many Marquette fans here was outstanding,'' Crean said. "Our guys felt very comfortable with that, and we appreciate the way they cheered for us the entire night.'' The Blue Demons shot just 33 percent the entire night and had 13 turnovers, but their toughness on the glass kept them in the game. DePaul outrebounded the Golden Eagles 40-38, and had a whopping edge on the offensive boards for much of the game. At one point, the Blue Demons had 15 offensive rebounds to Marquette's eight, and had a 14-6 advantage on second-chance points. But Marquette got more aggressive in the second half, getting 11 of its offensive rebounds and nine of its second-chance points. "It was simple,'' DePaul coach Dave Leitao said. "It was offensive rebounding on their part and our inability to get shots at the rim.'' Novak hurt them, too. The 6-foot-10 freshman had never made more than three 3-pointers before, but he was in one of those rare zones Wednesday night. With Marquette clinging to a 39-36 lead, he made one from the left side. Then another. And another. Then one from the right side, all of them hitting nothing but the net as Marquette took a 51-45 lead with 9:48 to play. "In high school, probably,'' Novak said of the last time he had a run like that. Added Wade: "Man, he was an unbelievable spark. We needed something from somewhere and Steve is a big-time shooter in practice. He finally shot it in the game. "I wanted him to keep shooting, but he didn't want to.'' The four 3s were enough. Robert Jackson converted a three-point play on Marquette's next possession to give the Golden Eagles a 54-45 lead -- their largest of the game to that point -- and the Blue Demons could never overcome it. "When we don't score on offense, we put a lot of pressure on defense,'' Hoskin said. "We have to score on offense. We have to.''
